e peasants. Some texts are addressed to a public and pan-Indian audience, others to a limited coterie of initiates in an esoteric sect, and still others are intended for a few women gathered in the courtyard for a household ceremony. The editor has reinforced this diversity by arranging the selections within several overarching themes and categories of discourse (hymns, rituals, narratives, and religious interactions), and encourages us to make our own connections.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aRELIGION / Hinduism / General.2bisacsh  aAkbar.  aAllah.  aArjuna.  aBrahmā.  aBuddhism.  aChristianity.  aDigambara Jains.  aGaṇeśa.  aGorakhnaāth.  aIndra.  aIslam.  aJainism.  aJesus.  aKabīr.  aKṛṣṇa.  aLakṣmī.  aMahābhārata.  aMurukaṉ.  aMuḥammad.  aNityānanda.  aNāth Siddhas.  aRādhā.  aRūpa Gosvāmī.  aSufism.  aTukārām.  aUpaniṣads.  aVedavyasa.  aYama.  abhakti.  acakra.  adehatattva.  adharma.  adhikr.  aguru.  ahaṭha yoga.  akuṇḍalinī.  amantra.  aparuvam.  aprema.  asahaja.  asaṃsāra.  asiddha.  aŚaiva Siddhānta.  aśiva-liṅga.1 aAsani, Ali, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeck, Guy Leon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrooks, Douglas Renfrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCort, John E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCutler, Norman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavidson, Ronald M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Richard H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDelmonico, Ned, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDharwadker, Vinay, econtrib